replies.bodyText:
When running this test locally I was curious to see what order threads were starting and stopping, so I added System.out.printlns at the beginning and end of each thread. The tiny extra delay seems to cause the readThread to perform its read before the write lock goes into place most of the time, so I get the error below, and the test fails. Did you run into this at all or on travis? I'm just a bit worried the test will flap from time to time.
Starting write
Starting read
Exception in thread "Thread-6" java.lang.NullPointerException
	at edu.unc.lib.dl.event.RepositoryPremisLoggerIT$5.run(RepositoryPremisLoggerIT.java:320)
	at java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:821)
Finished write

what I was running
        Runnable writeThreadRunnable = new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                System.out.println("Starting write");
                logger.writeEvents(anotherEvent);
                System.out.println("Finished write");
            }
        };
        Thread writeThread = new Thread(writeThreadRunnable);

        // start read thread
        List<String> premisNotes = new ArrayList<>();
        Runnable readThreadRunnable = new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                System.out.println("Starting read");
                Model logModel = retrieveLogger.getEventsModel();
                Resource logEventResc = logModel.getResource(anotherEvent.getURI());
                premisNotes.add(logEventResc.getProperty(Premis.note).getString());
                System.out.println("Finished read");
            }
        };

hmm, they are no longer happening concurrently are they? I'd guess the write thread finishes before read starts, and the 0 size check passes because its reading the list faster than the readThread reads from the logger. I guess I was thinking the threads should start at the same time, but there would be a sleep within the write thread instead:
Runnable writeThreadRunnable = new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                ReadWriteLock writeLock = pidLockManager.awaitWriteLock();
                logger.writeEvents(anotherEvent);
                Thread.sleep(25);
                writeLock.unlock();
            }
        };

